    <h1>About the WRC</h1>
    <p>    The World Rally Championship (WRC) is the highest level of international rally racing. It is a motorsport championship organized by the FIA, the same organization that runs Formula One.
    Unlike track racing, WRC events take place on closed public roads in different countries around the world.</p>
    <img src="images/GRYarisSnow.jpg" width="600" />
    <p> Drivers race one at a time against the clock on special stages that can be on gravel, snow, asphalt, mud, or ice. The driver with the lowest total time across all stages wins the rally.
    Each car has a driver and a co-driver. The co-driver reads pace notes, which describe the road ahead like turns, jumps, bumps, allowing the driver to go extremely fast even on unfamiliar roads.
    The championship takes place over multiple rallies during the season, and drivers and manufacturers earn points at each event to compete for the Drivers Championship and Manufacturers Championship titles.</p>
